<DOC><DOCNO> AP880229-0219 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 2214EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     02-29 0396</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0406</SECOND><HEAD>Tamil Women End Fast for Peace</HEAD><BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two Tamil women ended their 10-dayfast for peace Monday by taking water mixed with salt and sugar,witnesses said.   The hunger strikers, Anama David, 58, and Nesamma Vadival, 50,are members of the Tamil Mothers Front and had vowed not to eatuntil Indian troops ceased anti-rebel operations and Tamilseparatist guerrillas agreed to negotiations.   The witnesses spoke on condition of not being identified.   There was no indication the women's demands had been met.   An official at the Indian High Commission, or embassy, inColombo said Indian troops had reduced operations in northern andeastern Sri Lanka, zones where the Tamil minority form a majority.   But the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said themove was not related to appeals from the two women and he insistedthe scaling down did not amount to a cease-fire.   In New Delhi, Foreign Ministry spokesman GopalaswamiParthasarthy said operations against the Tamil rebels werecontinuing. He said India would agree to talks with the rebels onlyafter they surrendered their weapons.   A senior Sri Lankan military official, who also spoke oncondition that he not be identified,, said, however, that Indiansoldiers suspended operations in eastern Batticaloa district in abid to save the lives of the women, who were reported in poorcondition before abandoning their fast.   Officials at the Sri Lankan military headquarters in Colombosaid there was no fighting between Indian troops and Tamil rebelsfor the previous 24 hours. The officials, who cannot be identifiedunder briefing rules, said Indian soldiers were continuing searchoperations and patrols, however.   More than 45,000 Indian soldiers are in Sri Lanka to enforce anIndian-sponsored peace accord signed last July 29 with the SriLankan government to try to end the rebels' four-year war for anindependent Tamil homeland in the northern zone of this island offIndia's southern coast.   A spokesman for the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, thelargest rebel group, said Sunday the Tigers were prepared forunconditional talks with the Indian government.   More than 8,000 people have been killed in Sri Lanka since theTamil insurrection began. Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, comprise18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people. They claim theSinhalese Buddhist majority discriminate against them.</TEXT></DOC>